(40, 26, 29, 19, 40, 3, 3, 'new', 'Newness and Praise Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of ''newness'' in both passages. Matthew speaks of drinking ''new'' in the kingdom, while Psalms mentions a ''new song'' of praise.', 'theme', 0.349, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 29, 42, 22, 15, 18, NULL, 'Connection of Kingdom References', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of the kingdom of God and the future fulfillment of Jesus'' promise to share in the fruit of the vine. They highlight a significant moment during the Last Supper, indicating a future celebration in God''s kingdom.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 29, 42, 22, 29, 30, 'my Father's kingdom', 'Connection of Kingdom and Fellowship', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of fellowship in the kingdom. Matthew speaks of drinking with the disciples in the kingdom, while Luke mentions eating and drinking at the table in the kingdom.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 29, 40, 13, 43, 43, 'in my Father's kingdom', 'Connection of Kingdom References', 'This connection highlights the theme of the kingdom of the Father in both passages. Matthew 26:29 speaks of drinking in the Father''s kingdom, while Matthew 13:43 describes the righteous shining in that same kingdom.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 30, 40, 21, 1, 1, 'mount of Olives', 'Journey to the Mount of Olives', 'Both passages emphasize the Mount of Olives as a significant location in Jesus'' journey. The first passage describes the disciples going to the Mount of Olives after singing a hymn, while the second passage mentions their approach to the Mount of Olives as they near Jerusalem.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 30, 42, 22, 39, 39, 'mount of Olives', 'Journey to the Mount of Olives', 'Both passages emphasize the Mount of Olives as a significant location. In Matthew, the disciples go there after singing a hymn, while Luke describes Jesus going there as was his custom.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 30, 49, 5, 19, 20, 'sung an hymn', 'Connection of Singing and Thanksgiving', 'Both passages emphasize the act of singing, with Matthew highlighting the singing of a hymn and Ephesians encouraging singing and giving thanks. This connection highlights the importance of music in worship and gratitude to God.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 30, 41, 14, 26, 31, 'they had sung an hymn', 'Connection of Hymn and Departure', 'Both passages emphasize the act of singing a hymn before leaving for the Mount of Olives. This connection highlights a shared moment of worship and transition as they move towards the events of Jesus'' arrest.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 30, 42, 21, 37, 37, 'mount of Olives', 'Connection through Mount of Olives', 'Both passages emphasize the Mount of Olives as a significant location. In Matthew, it is where Jesus goes after singing a hymn, while in Luke, it is noted as the place he retreats to at night.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 30, 43, 14, 31, 31, 'went out into the mount of Olives', 'Departure and Obedience Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of leaving. In Matthew, they ''went out'' after singing, while in John, Jesus instructs them to ''Arise, let us go hence.'' This connection highlights the theme of obedience to the Father''s command as they prepare to depart.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 30, 43, 18, 1, 4, 'went out into the mount of Olives', 'Journey to the Garden', 'This connection highlights the sequence of events as Jesus and his disciples move from singing a hymn to entering the garden. Both passages emphasize the transition from a moment of worship to the impending betrayal and arrest.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 31, 38, 13, 7, 7, NULL, 'Connection Between Shepherd and Scattering', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of the shepherd being smitten and the scattering of the sheep. Matthew directly quotes Zechariah, linking the events of Jesus'' impending betrayal to the prophecy of the shepherd''s fate.', 'quotation', 0.685, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 31, 41, 14, 27, 28, 'All ye shall be offended because of me this night', 'Connection of Jesus'' Prediction', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus predicting the scattering of his disciples. They share the phrase ''All ye shall be offended because of me this night,'' linking their messages about the disciples'' reaction to his impending arrest.', 'parallel', 0.45399999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 31, 43, 16, 32, 32, 'the sheep of the flock shall be scattered abroad', 'Disciples'' Scattering Foretold', 'This connection highlights the theme of the disciples being scattered. Both passages emphasize the impending abandonment of Jesus by his followers.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 31, 26, 34, 5, 6, 'the sheep of the flock shall be scattered abroad', 'Scattering of the Sheep', 'This connection highlights the theme of the scattering of the sheep due to the absence of a shepherd. Both passages emphasize the consequences of this scattering, with Jesus referencing the prophecy in Ezekiel about the flock being scattered.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 31, 19, 69, 20, 20, 'sheep of the flock shall be scattered', 'Connection of Suffering and Abandonment', 'This connection highlights the theme of abandonment and suffering. In Matthew, Jesus predicts the scattering of his followers, while in Psalms, the speaker expresses deep sorrow and lack of comfort. Both passages convey a sense of isolation in times of distress.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 31, 19, 38, 11, 11, 'the sheep of the flock shall be scattered abroad', 'Isolation in Suffering', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of abandonment during times of distress. In Matthew, Jesus predicts that his followers will scatter, while in Psalms, the speaker laments that friends and family stand aloof in suffering.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 31, 40, 24, 9, 10, 'shall be offended', 'Connection of Offense and Betrayal', 'This connection highlights the theme of being ''offended'' in both passages. In Matthew 26:31, Jesus predicts that his followers will be offended and scattered, while Matthew 24:9-10 speaks of many being offended and betraying one another.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 32, 40, 28, 10, 10, 'go before you into Galilee', 'Galilee Resurrection Connection', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' promise to meet his disciples in Galilee after his resurrection. Both passages emphasize the significance of Galilee as the location where the disciples will see him again.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 32, 40, 28, 16, 16, 'go before you into Galilee', 'Resurrection and Galilee Connection', 'This connection highlights the fulfillment of Jesus'' promise to meet the disciples in Galilee after His resurrection. Both passages emphasize the significance of Galilee as the appointed location for this meeting.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 32, 42, 18, 33, 34, 'I am risen again', 'Resurrection and Understanding', 'Both passages emphasize the resurrection on the third day. Matthew indicates Jesus will rise again, while Luke notes the disciples did not understand this prophecy. This connection highlights the theme of resurrection and the disciples'' lack of comprehension.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 32, 41, 9, 9, 10, 'risen again', 'Resurrection and Galilee Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of resurrection. Matthew mentions the resurrection and a subsequent meeting in Galilee, while Mark discusses the command to keep the resurrection secret until it occurs.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 32, 41, 14, 28, 28, 'I will go before you into Galilee', 'Resurrection and Galilee Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the resurrection and the promise to go before the disciples into Galilee. This connection highlights the continuity in Jesus'' message about His resurrection and subsequent actions.', 'parallel', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 32, 43, 21, 1, 14, 'I will go before you into Galilee', 'Resurrection and Appearance in Galilee', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' promise to meet his disciples in Galilee after his resurrection, as stated in Matthew 26:32. John 21:1-14 recounts the fulfillment of this promise, where Jesus appears to his disciples at the Sea of Tiberias, which is in Galilee.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 32, 46, 15, 6, 6, 'I am risen again', 'Resurrection and Appearances', 'This connection highlights the theme of resurrection and subsequent appearances. Matthew 26:32 mentions Jesus rising and going to Galilee, while 1 Corinthians 15:6 refers to Him being seen by many after His resurrection.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 33, 42, 22, 33, 33, 'yet will I never be offended', 'Peter''s Commitment to Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize Peter''s strong commitment to Jesus, as he declares his readiness to stand by Him despite potential danger. This connection highlights Peter''s boldness in asserting his loyalty, whether in refusing to be offended or in expressing willingness to face imprisonment and death.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 33, 19, 17, 5, 5, 'yet will I never be offended', 'Faithfulness in Trials', 'This connection highlights the theme of steadfastness in the face of challenges. Peter''s declaration of unwavering loyalty parallels the plea for guidance to avoid slipping in one''s path.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 33, 19, 119, 116, 117, 'never be offended', 'Faith and Assurance in Trials', 'This connection highlights the theme of steadfastness in faith during trials. Peter''s declaration of unwavering loyalty parallels the psalmist''s plea for support to avoid shame in hope.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 33, 20, 16, 18, 19, NULL, 'Pride and Humility Connection', 'This connection highlights Peter''s pride in claiming he will never be offended, which aligns with the warning in Proverbs about pride leading to destruction. Both passages emphasize the importance of humility over haughtiness.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 33, 20, 20, 6, 6, NULL, 'Faithfulness and Human Proclamation', 'Both passages emphasize the nature of human faithfulness and self-proclamation. Peter''s declaration of unwavering loyalty contrasts with the idea that most men proclaim their own goodness, suggesting a deeper truth about true faithfulness.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
